<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Submission from Oxfordshire County Council (FDC17)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Submission from</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Oxfordshire County Council (FDC17)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Oxfordshire County Council is pleased to provide evidence to the CLG Select Committee's inquiry on devolution to English Cities and City Regions. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">This is a timely inquiry given the recognition by the government through the City Deal and Strategic Economi</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">c Plan processes that creating the conditions for sustainable economic growth is overwhelmingly a bottom-up process, driven by local expertise and local economic actors, not top-down policymaking.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> Taken together with the recent report by Lord Heseltine, an</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">d the Department for Communities and Local Government's high profile commitment to localism, there is much cause for optimism.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">It is our firm belief that both the imbalance of devolution within the United Kingdom, and the scale of centralisation compared </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">to other develop</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ed countries, are urgent issues, and ones which it is within the power of central and local government, working together, to address.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">About Oxfordshire</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Oxfordshire is a diverse and dynamic county, home to 661,000 people and over 30,000 bu</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">sinesses. The co</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">unty has a competitive economy -</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> the unemployment rate is one of the lowest in the country, and the number of young people unemployed has returned to pre-recession levels. In total, Oxfordshire’s economy contributes £15.5 billion a year to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the national economy. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The vibrancy of Oxfordshire’s economy is inextricably linked to the activities of its two universities, its teaching hospital and research trust - which is one of the largest in the UK - and the concentration of science and research</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> activity in the south of the county. Science Vale UK, the county’s science and technology heart, is larger than that of Cambridge and, indeed, larger even than that of MIT in the USA. Together</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> these give Oxfordshire</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> the largest concentration of Research </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">D</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">evelopment</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> activity in Western Europe.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Oxfordshire’s bio-technology sector has grown 14% since 2008, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> the space technology cluster located at Harwell i</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s growing rapidly - including</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> the European Space Agency and the International Space Innovation C</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">entre. Along with the neighbouring counties of Berkshire and Buckinghamshire, Oxfordshire forms part of one of the highest concentrations of high-tech employment in Europe. In addition, we are home to globally recognised, prestigious brands such as BMW Min</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">i and Oxford University Press. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Notwithstanding our overall prosperity, the county faces some important challenges. Oxfordshire has a growing and changing population – more people, and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">in particular </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">more</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">older people, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">especially</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> in rural areas. The county has pockets of significant </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">deprivation, with eighteen local areas in the county amongst the 20% most deprived in England. Rural isolation also affects the lives of many people living outside our major towns and city. Oxfordshire</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> is also one of the most expensive places to live in the country, and prices in Oxford City are the second highest in the country</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> outside of London. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">In 2012/13 Oxfordshire County Council’s gross expenditure was £972.8m. With this money the council provi</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">des 80% of local government se</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">rvices in the county, including children's services, roads and transport, education, adul</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">t social care, libraries and museums, and waste disposal and recycling.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Overall Comments</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">In the current context the key driver of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">devolved arrangements is to promote measures which deliver economic growth, and therefore the most logical structures for doing so are those built around functional economic areas.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Oxfordshire County Council is</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, however,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> concerned at the language used in </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the Committee's call for evidence, which implies an uncritical acceptance of the view that groups of authorities serving large urban areas are more suited to devolution than authorities serving more mixed geographies such as Oxfordshire. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">We wou</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">d challen</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ge the wisdom of this. T</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">here is potentially a great deal to gain in allowing more independence for, and innovation from, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">democratically accountable local </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">authorities such as Oxfordshire.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Our view is that there is no barrier to a broadly symmetrical devol</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ution offer across England, even if the detail and pace may vary according to local circumstances. The Government's recognition that further areas, including county geographies, can benefit from "Wave 2" city deals is welcome. Following this, devolution me</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">asures should be considered across England, rather than an assumption of "core city first" devolution.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">In response to the Committee's specific questions:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">H</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ow ‘devolved’ areas would be defined geographically and set up;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Across the overwhelming majority of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">England the most effective and efficient </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">geographic model fo</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">r devolution would </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">exhibit coterminosity with</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> existing</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> units of local government - minimising start-up costs, additional bureaucracy, and organisational turbulence. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">In some areas, this would </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">most appropriately be delivered through groups of authorities on a scale similar to Local Enterprise Partnerships</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. In Oxfordshire</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> the functional economic geography clearly speaks to a unit coterminous with the county </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">boundary</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, and indeed the Oxfordshire L</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">EP was established on this basis</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. In other areas long-standing successful partnerships across local boundaries (eg Partnership for Urban South Hampshire, Enterprise M3, the Capital to Coast partnership) demonstrate the importance of working on the basis of</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> functional economic geography.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Devolved areas should seek to maximise their role as leaders of place, and representatives of local people and businesses. In Oxfordshire's case devolution on a county geography would have the benefit of reflecting an exist</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ing administrative area, with which local people and businesses feel a sense of identity and belonging</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, and within which political leadership is already established</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">H</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ow public services, including employment, skills and welfare, should be organised to comp</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">lement devolution;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> wide</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> range of public sector services</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, including but not limited to those</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> focused on helping people secure appropriate employment could not simply be 'organised to complement devolution', but could themselves be largely devolved. Where </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">possible</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> this should be done in a way which minimises the cost of bureau</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">cracy</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, and maximises democratic accountability to local people</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. G</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">enerally this will be through devolution to existing units of local government at a strategic scale. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Where </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">such devo</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">lution is not possible</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">relevant public services </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">should be organised flexibly, with lead managers for local areas able to adjust policy and spending to account for local circumstances, and work in close partnership </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">across</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> local</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> public, private, and vol</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">untary sectors.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">A particular example would be maximising the sharing of information, data, and forward plans be</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">tween the local DWP and local democratic bodies working to deliver skills training, apprenticeships, education and growth.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">H</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ow ‘devolved’ areas</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> would be governed, including the role of business in decision making;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">H</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ow ‘devolved’ areas would be held to account;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">A range of models exist for specific 'devolved partnership' activity - where devolution to a specific purpose is established, such as</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> thro</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ugh the City Deal process. T</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">his has been undertaken through Economic Prosperity Boards, Statutory Joint Committees, Combined Authorities, and</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> other</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> bespoke arrangements</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">In Oxfordshire's case a range of partnership arrangements exist around local leadersh</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ip, strategic planning and infrastructure, and economic growth</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. A</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> key </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">benefit of the City Deal process has been to drive our work in </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">bring</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> these together, maximising clear and consistent decision-making, and minimising the time </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">commitment required from </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">private sector partners. It would not be productive to create a further, separate, meeting for the governance of each initiative.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The involvement of business is important, particularly in policy areas which directly contribute to economic growth, and clos</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">e working </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">with </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">local businesses on buildi</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ng a robust local evidence base</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> will be crucial to successful devolution on economic issues.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> Governance models need the confidence of business, and therefore should where possible be stabl</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">e over the medium term</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">with</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> settled</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> local arrangements provided with some protection f</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">rom short-term national initiatives.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">In some cases 'Deal-based devolution' will also require</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> accountability to central government</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> and t</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">hrough Ministers to Parliament. This is </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">particularly</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> th</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">e case</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> for activity deliver</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ed locally but funded centrally. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Devolution should not result in reduced public accountability, and for devolved spending decisions the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">primary accountability should be to local residents at the ballot box.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">T</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">he strength of the ev</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">idence that devolution would lead to economic growth, local improvement and better local governance, including examples of what areas could do with their new powers such as use them to invest in infrastructure and local services;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Oxfordshire County Council</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> and local partners are in the final stages of negotiating a City Deal, which aims to maximise the benefit to Oxfordshire and the UK of the knowledge economy businesses and scientific research clustered in Oxfordshire. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The evidence thus far from City Dea</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ls agreed in the first wave is that imaginative partnership between central and local government, and the private sector, can play a valuable part in </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">delivering economic growth, simplifying public sector arrangements locally, and clarifying the relationshi</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">p between Whitehall and local areas.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">T</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">he impact on areas not included in any new devolution arrangements, including those on cities’ borders and those affected by resulting changes to national financial equalisation and distributive arrangements;</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Overall</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Oxfordshire exhibits the characteristics of a successful city-region economy, and additional devolution is being sought in particular to maximise the benefits for Oxfordshire and the UK of the knowledge economy</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. This knowledge economy is</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> driven by Oxford'</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s universities, other research institutions in the county, and the clusters of high-tech businesses these have generated and attracted.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The administrative area of Oxfordshire County Council is fortunate in being both coterminous with a Local Enterprise Pa</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">rtnership, and closely aligned to a functional economic geography as measured by, for example, travel to work areas. While recognising that in some parts of the country the borders of metropolitan cities generate an additional complexity, Oxfordshire is fo</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">rtunate in that no area should need to be excluded from a local devolution arrangement.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The question of working across boundaries will depend on the nature of the economic opportunity - indeed th</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ey may vary for a single place. For example </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Oxfordshire's st</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">rength in high-end automotive engineering speaks to a different set of neighbours and a different supply chain geography from its strength in earth sciences. In a number of cases the cluster may be fun</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ctional rather than geographic: </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">in the knowledge econom</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">y lack of physical proximity should be no barrier to joint working. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">W</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">hether reform of the existing system (for example, re-banding council tax, revaluing business rates, Community Budgets, Government grants, formulas and taxes such as stamp duty) would be</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> a precursor to, or run along with, large-scale constitutional change.</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">While a coherent process of devolution would be preferable, we see a significant risk that such a transition would be hampered by "chicken and egg" issues. The suggestion that devolutio</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">n should be delayed simply because it is 'untidy' sits uncomfortably with the English constitutional tradition of incremental change.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Devolution of power, taken to mean an increase in the quantity and importance of decisions taken locally, needs to run al</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ongside devolution of revenue-raising powers, since in an era of austerity financial circumstances form a key part of decision-making.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">While a range of positive outcomes can be demonstrated from the Oxfordshire City Deal negotiation process, and our expectation is of a positive outcome for Oxfordshire residents and businesses, an opportunity to go much further was missed. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">It appears tha</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">t the default position of central government in response to local proposals for devolution remains far too often to justify the status quo, rather than consider the potential benefits. In the spirit of the Heseltine report, we feel that government should w</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">elcome proposals more positively when they come forward - whether as part of a formal negotiation process, or as a result of local innovation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">On the details, the Committee invite</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">d</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> views on:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">what taxes might be devolved—for example council tax, stamp duty </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">and business rates;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">the scope for areas to introduce new taxes and funding methods such as bonds and crowd-sourcing, fees and charges; and</span></li></ul><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Options for providing local government with additional revenue-raising options should be broadly-based, and transpare</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">nt. Placing the above mechanisms under local democratic control would be welcome. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Oxfordshire County Council would especially welcome:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Increased flexibility for local areas to determine appropriate fees and charges for service, to best suit local circum</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">stances and minimise the burden on taxpayers. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Local control over council tax - not only flexibility around the overall level of tax, but also around discounts applied (for example the option of limiting the single person discount to lower bands).</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Further </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">meaningful devolution of the proceeds of growth, whether through greater local control of, and share in, business rates growth, or localisation of some revenue from other national taxes (sales or income taxes, for example).</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The final option could be deliv</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ered for high-growth areas undertaking additional investment to support growth, particularly as part of 'deal-based devolution', through a gain share mechanism. This is a </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">financial model projecting the difference between the current growth trajectory and t</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">he predicted growth trajectory following the implementation of the policy interventions. This would approximate for the growth in tax revenue (which could be business rates, sales tax, income tax, or some combination of taxes), and allocate a local share.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">W</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">hat changes should be made to “devolved” authorities’ borrowing powers;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Local government has a strong track record of responsible borrowing to ensure appropriate investment. Oxfordshire County Council would support changes to borrowing rules which increas</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ed the flexibility of local authorities to make long-term investment decisions in the</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> interests of their local areas. I</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">n particular</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> we would support changes which enable borrowing designed </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">to secure economic growth and provide critical infrastructure, and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">to deliver long-term savings.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">T</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">he extent to which high-performing areas would be expected to redistribute their proceeds of growth via the Treasury.</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Oxfordshire County Council recognises that the tax system cannot be wholly localised, since there will </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">always be a need for some redistribution to take place to support those areas which do not have a buoyant local tax base.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The two key elements to ensuring that this is an effective system are firstly ensuring that redistribution of the proceeds of growth</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> is not so sharp as to discourage investment, and</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> secondly</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> ensuring that the system is as simp</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">le and transparent as possible. This would </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">encourage certainty and ensure the independence of civil servants is not compromised.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">9 January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>